      <h2>What Is an Industrial Static Eliminator?</h2>
      <p>
        An <strong>industrial static eliminator</strong> is a device that generates ions to neutralize static charge on production materials and substrates. Unlike grounding equipment, which only works on conductive objects, static eliminators neutralize charge on insulators — films, panels, PCBs, and plastics — by flooding the area with balanced positive and negative ions. The ions are attracted to the charged surface and cancel the charge.
      </p>
      <p>
        Industrial static eliminators are available in several form factors: bar-type ionizers that mount above conveyors, fan-based blowers for workstations, and rod-type units for machine integration. Each is suited to different production configurations and throughput requirements.
      </p>

      <h3>Why Industrial Environments Need Static Eliminators</h3>
      <p>
        Static charge is an unavoidable byproduct of industrial production. Any time materials move, separate, or contact each other, charge is generated by the triboelectric effect. At production line speeds, charge accumulation on insulating substrates is rapid and can reach levels that cause serious process problems:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>ESD damage to components</strong> — discharge events invisible to operators permanently damage semiconductor junctions, gate oxides, and metallization in ICs and discrete devices</li>
        <li><strong>Particle adhesion and contamination</strong> — charged surfaces attract airborne dust and particles that cannot be removed by downstream cleaning, causing optical defects and surface quality failures</li>
        <li><strong>Process jams and misfeeds</strong> — static cling between sheets, webs, or film layers causes misfeeds in printing, converting, and lamination equipment</li>
        <li><strong>Coating and ink adhesion failures</strong> — static charge disrupts the wetting and adhesion of coatings, inks, and adhesives on plastic and film substrates</li>
        <li><strong>Operator shocks and discomfort</strong> — high charge levels on equipment and materials discharge through operators, causing discomfort and distraction</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Industrial Static Eliminator Applications by Industry</h3>

      <h4>Electronics and PCB Manufacturing</h4>
      <p>
        Electronics manufacturing requires static control at every stage where ESD-sensitive components are handled. Ionizing bars positioned at conveyor infeed and outfeed points neutralize charge on PCBs before screen printing, component placement, and inspection. The combination of grounded work surfaces, wrist straps, and ionizing equipment creates a complete ESD-protected production environment.
      </p>
      <p>
        For SMT assembly lines, inline ionizers with conveyor speed matching provide continuous static control without interrupting the production flow. DGSDK's <a href="/products/static-eliminator/st-g-series">ST-G series</a> intelligent ionizing bars are suited for this application, with balance monitoring and alarm output to maintain control without manual checking.
      </p>

      <h4>Display and Optical Film Manufacturing</h4>
      <p>
        Display manufacturing involves some of the most demanding static control requirements in industrial production. Polarizer films, diffusion sheets, and glass panels are large, highly insulating, and transported at conveyor speeds where charge accumulates rapidly. A 500mm-wide polarizer sheet moving at 20 m/min can reach surface voltages of several thousand volts within a few meters of travel.
      </p>
      <p>
        At these charge levels, airborne particles are attracted to the surface before any cleaning step, and ESD events during handling can damage display driver ICs and thin-film transistor arrays. Full-width ionizing bars spanning the conveyor width — matched to the conveyor speed — are the standard solution for this application. DGSDK supplies bar-length static eliminators for display-line applications.
      </p>

      <h4>Printing and Converting</h4>
      <p>
        Printing presses and web converting lines generate charge continuously from high-speed paper and film movement through rollers, nip points, and unwinding stations. Static-related problems include: sheet misfeeds in sheetfed presses, web breaks from static cling in reel-to-reel converters, operator shocks at take-off and delivery stations, and ink jet deflection in inkjet systems.
      </p>
      <p>
        Static eliminators for printing are typically mounted at the point of charge generation — near rollers, nip points, and sheeting cutters — and at delivery stacks where sheet-to-sheet static cling causes jams. The high throughput of printing equipment requires fast-response ionizers positioned close to the target web.
      </p>

      <h4>Plastics and Injection Molding</h4>
      <p>
        Injection-molded plastic parts carry high surface charges from the mold and the demolding process. This charge attracts airborne dust and contamination at a critical point — just as the part comes off the tool and before any surface inspection or packaging. Ion blowers directed at parts as they exit the mold remove surface charge and reduce particle attraction during the period before inspection.
      </p>
      <p>
        For plastic film extrusion and sheet lines, bar-type ionizers at the extrusion die and winding station neutralize charge that would otherwise cause inter-layer cling in wound rolls and contamination on clear optical-grade films.
      </p>

      <h4>Cleanroom and Optical Component Manufacturing</h4>
      <p>
        Cleanroom environments present specific requirements for static eliminators: low ozone output to maintain air quality, low particle generation from the ionizer itself, and compatibility with laminar airflow patterns. DC-type ionizing bars (steady-state or pulse DC) are preferred in cleanrooms because they produce less ozone than AC ionizers and generate a more stable ion output.
      </p>
      <p>
        In optical component manufacturing — lenses, filters, gratings, and coated glass — even minute particle contamination causes coating failures and rejects. Static eliminators positioned ahead of each coating and inspection station maintain surface cleanliness by preventing particle adhesion between process steps.
      </p>

      <h3>Selecting an Industrial Static Eliminator</h3>
      <p>
        The right industrial static eliminator for your application depends on several factors:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Application type</strong> — conveyor line vs. workstation vs. machine-integrated determines whether you need a bar, ion blower, or compact rod-type unit</li>
        <li><strong>Coverage width</strong> — the ionizing bar must span the full width of the material to neutralize charge across the entire surface</li>
        <li><strong>Working distance</strong> — the gap between the ionizer and the target affects performance; tighter spacing improves neutralization at higher line speeds</li>
        <li><strong>Line speed</strong> — high-speed lines require pulse DC ionizers with fast response times positioned closer to the substrate</li>
        <li><strong>Environment</strong> — cleanroom applications require low-ozone DC models; outdoor or corrosive environments require sealed construction</li>
        <li><strong>Monitoring requirements</strong> — critical lines benefit from intelligent ionizers with balance monitoring and alarm output</li>
      </ul>

